# Coding Conventions

## Input Validation

- Validate all external input with Zod schemas. No exceptions.
- Define schemas co-located with the module that consumes them.
- Reuse shared schemas from a central `schemas/` directory when applicable.

## Module Boundaries

- No cross-domain imports. Each domain is self-contained.
- Use `providers/` for shared concerns that span multiple domains (e.g., logging, config, auth context).
- If two domains need to communicate, use a defined interface or event contract — never direct imports.

## Logging

- Structured logging only. Use the project's logging utility.
- No `console.log`, `console.warn`, or `console.error` in production code.
- Every log entry must include: level, timestamp, correlation ID, and contextual metadata.
- Sensitive data (PII, PHI, tokens, passwords) must never appear in log output.

## File Structure

- File size limit: 300 lines. If a file exceeds this, split it into focused modules.
- One export concern per file. Avoid "god files" that handle multiple responsibilities.
- Group related files by feature/domain, not by technical type.

## Documentation

- Every public function must have a JSDoc comment describing its purpose, parameters, return value, and thrown errors.
- Complex business logic must include inline comments explaining the "why," not the "what."
- Update documentation when changing function signatures or behavior.

## Testing

- Tests are required for all files in `services/` and `hooks/` directories.
- Test file naming: `[module].test.ts` co-located with the source file.
- Minimum test coverage: happy path, primary error path, and edge cases.
- Tests must be deterministic — no reliance on external services, time, or random values without mocking.

## Branch and Commit Conventions

- Branch naming: `[linear-id]-short-description` (e.g., `ENG-1234-add-user-auth`).
- Commit messages: `[LINEAR-ID] description of change` (e.g., `[ENG-1234] Add JWT validation middleware`).
- Keep commits atomic — one logical change per commit.

## PR Conventions

- Link the Linear issue in the PR description.
- PR description must include: what changed, why it changed, and how to test it.
- No PR may be merged without passing all CI checks and at least one peer review.

## Technical Debt

- No `TODO` or `FIXME` comments without a linked Linear issue (e.g., `// TODO [ENG-5678]: Refactor after migration`).
- Unlinked TODOs will be flagged and blocked in code review.

## Error Handling

- Use Result types (e.g., `Result<T, E>`) or explicit error boundaries for all operations that can fail.
- Never swallow errors silently. Every caught error must be logged or re-thrown.
- User-facing error messages must be generic. Internal error details go to structured logs only.

## Async Operations

- All async operations must have a defined timeout.
- Retry logic must be explicit: define max retries, backoff strategy, and failure behavior.
- Use abort controllers or cancellation tokens for long-running operations.
- Document the expected latency and failure mode for every external call.
